On the 18th of July, birthday of Canadian composer and acoustic ecologist R. Murray Schafer, we celebrate #WorldListeningDay. It is a day to really listen – what does the world sound like with or without the noises that are imposed on us by technology, industry, and our own selves? 

In celebration of soundscape in Zion, we offer a short video highlighting some of the evening murmurings you may hear if you take a stroll at sunset or camp under the stars. Of course, these are not the only sounds we experience and contribute to. The earth is never silent, however we can all do our part to reduce unnecessary volume by hiking with headphones rather than speakers (or simply the music of the park), keep conversations quiet, and enjoy experiences that may be very different from our day to day lives. 

What is the soundscape like where you live? Our mornings are punctuated with rustling leaves as wind blows down the canyon, while afternoons are dominated by rumbling shuttle buses, people chatting, and gravel and sand scrunching underfoot. Depending on the time of day or year that you visit, you’ll have a unique auditory experience! 

NPS Video/ Montage of five short videos of different areas of the park, overlaid with natural sounds. First, a small waterfall trickles into a pool. Next, the video pans across the cliffs including and around Angels Landing and the Great White Throne with various bird calls. The focus shifts to the shallow river with cliffs in the background, and the trickling of the river can be heard. Next, we head up the West Rim trail to see a small chipmunk scurry away, panning up along the cliffs, leaving the trail behind. Lastly, we find ourselves at Scout Lookout, overlooking the floor of the canyon from high above. The video ends by panning up to a partly cloudy periwinkle and pink sunset.

Join Ranger Kristina as she teaches you how some lizards in Zion National Park avoid becoming lunch! In this video, we talk about chuckwalla, desert spiny lizards, western whiptails, greater short horned lizards, and plateau lizards.

Visit the park website to learn more about reptiles here: https://www.nps.gov/zion/learn/nature/reptiles.htm

"Piglet noticed that even though he had a very small heart, it could hold a rather large amount of gratitude." — A.A. Milne

What are you thankful for? Share in the comments! 

We are thankful for the healing power of nature. Here is a daily dose from Zion! Settle into this extended scene in Zion Canyon, filmed in Spring of 2020. 

This series of videos gives people a chance to spend a few peaceful minutes in the park. In this video, imagine sitting under the cottonwood trees on the floor of Zion Canyon and looking up at the canyon walls around you. The red sandstone peak in the scene is named Mount Spry and can be seen near Canyon Junction.

Utah State Route 9 (SR-9) through Zion National Park will be closing nightly from 10:00 PM MDT until 6:00 AM MDT starting July 26, 2021. During the scheduled maintenance, a full closure to ALL vehicle traffic will be implemented Monday through Thursday from 10:00PM MDT to 6:00 AM MDT. 

No construction is scheduled to occur over the weekends from Friday 6:00 AM MDT to Monday 10:00 PM MDT. Proceeding with maintenance and full closures at night is anticipated to decrease traffic congestion, reduce visitor impacts, as well as facilitate safe and efficient working environment for the road maintenance operating heavy equipment. 

Alternate east and west routes are available via Highway 59 from Hurricane, Utah to Fredonia, Arizona and Highway 14 from Cedar City, Utah to Long Valley Junction and Highway 89.

node.text:
Did you know that there are California condors in Zion? California condors are the largest flying land birds in North America with a wingspan of up to 9.5 feet (3 meters) and we have a pair that has successfully nested right here the park!

Back in November of 2020, Zion’s Vertical Habitat Specialist took a break from monitoring cliff roosting bats to get up close and personal with the condor nest. Due to the time it takes for condor parents to raise their chick, they only nest every other year which allowed a perfect window of time to do a little nest exploration and clean up while the birds were away. 

One of the many threats that condors face, is the ingestion of microtrash, which was unfortunately found inside of the nest along with many larger pieces of trash. Many visitors drop trash from the popular Angels Landing trail, which is right near the condor nest. Condors are very curious birds and can be attracted to the shine of a plastic water bottle or a pair of sunglasses and even bring it back to the nest and try to feed it to their chick which can easily be fatal as they are unable to digest it. 

Do your part to help protect these magnificent birds, and if you plan to visit Zion or hike Angels Landing, make sure your trash is disposed of properly and your items are secured so they do not end up in a condors nest!

 #LeaveNoTrace #RecreateResponsibly 

NPS Photos/Sierra Martin

As we continue #LatinoConservationWeek, meet Ranger Rendall, and learn more about what it means to be a Wilderness ranger!

English transcript: Hello! My name is Rendall Seely, I am a Wilderness Ranger in Zion National Park, a Leave No Trace Master Educator, and a bit of a dinosaur fanatic. 
Two of the main responsibilities that I have as a ranger are: issuing permits to visitors for backpacking, canyoneering, and hiking trips, and going on patrols into the Zion Wilderness. 
I help write the content that is published in our Wilderness Guide newspaper and informational handouts. I am also a web author for the park, helping assure that the Wilderness information you read on our park website is current and easy to navigate. 
Traveling into the Zion Wilderness, even on short trips, can be very challenging and requires careful planning before you begin. Your safety depends on your own good judgment, adequate preparation, and constant observation.

#EncuentraTuParque #FindYourPark

On the 18th of July, birthday of Canadian composer and acoustic ecologist R. Murray Schafer, we celebrate #WorldListeningDay. It is a day to really listen – what does the world sound like with or without the noises that are imposed on us by technology, industry, and our own selves? 

In celebration of soundscape in Zion, we offer a short video highlighting some of the evening murmurings you may hear if you take a stroll at sunset or camp under the stars. Of course, these are not the only sounds we experience and contribute to. The earth is never silent, however we can all do our part to reduce unnecessary volume by hiking with headphones rather than speakers (or simply the music of the park), keep conversations quiet, and enjoy experiences that may be very different from our day to day lives. 

What is the soundscape like where you live? Our mornings are punctuated with rustling leaves as wind blows down the canyon, while afternoons are dominated by rumbling shuttle buses, people chatting, and gravel and sand scrunching underfoot. Depending on the time of day or year that you visit, you’ll have a unique auditory experience! 

NPS Video/ Montage of five short videos of different areas of the park, overlaid with natural sounds. First, a small waterfall trickles into a pool. Next, the video pans across the cliffs including and around Angels Landing and the Great White Throne with various bird calls. The focus shifts to the shallow river with cliffs in the background, and the trickling of the river can be heard. Next, we head up the West Rim trail to see a small chipmunk scurry away, panning up along the cliffs, leaving the trail behind. Lastly, we find ourselves at Scout Lookout, overlooking the floor of the canyon from high above. The video ends by panning up to a partly cloudy periwinkle and pink sunset.

It's #LatinoConservationWeek! Meet Ranger Jesse, and learn a little about what he does in the park.

English transcript: Hello and good afternoon, my name is Jesse Portillo and I am an Interpretive Park Ranger here at Zion National Park.

The responsibilities of this position include delivering education programs to the public, supplementing visitors with park information, and more importantly, natural resource protection. This consists of roving trails in the park or helping other divisions. 

My favorite thing about working in Zion is helping Spanish-speaking families connect to the park. Being a person of Latino heritage and a bilingual interpreter, it's important to connect my community to the public lands since we are underrepresented in the outdoors. 
I also enjoy delivering education programs, allowng visitors the opportunity to deeply connect with Zion's natural and historical resources. 

#EncuentraTuParque #FindYourPark

node.text:
🌲“There’s nothing wrong with having a tree as a friend” - Bob Ross🌲

No there isn’t, Bob Ross, no there isn’t! 

In Zion’s higher elevations, the Ponderosa Pine grows with the ability to tower over 150 feet, making it a very tall friend indeed. Rarely does the Ponderosa Pine reach heights of that magnitude out on the slickrock of Zion’s higher elevations. Rather, their growth tends to become more stunted and twisted, forming fantastic shapes that lend the appearance of the Japanese Bonsai. 

The Ponderosa Pine is one of the major species used for dendrochronology, or in other words tree ring dating. This allows for the understanding of historic climate patterns. Using dendrochronology has given archaeologists the ability to date Native American ruins by reading the width of tree rings from the roof beams.

One could say that the Ponderosa’s hidden talents is its resistance to fire. The smaller trees may succumb to fire while only raging wildfires known as firestorms have the ability to take down the larger trees. The thick, heavy bark of the Ponderosa acts like armor, to protect the phloem layer, or life source, of the tree. If all the needles are burned off and the phloem layer remains protected, the tree will still survive. 

The age long dispute of the Ponderosa Pine is what scent their orange bark exudes - it off the sweet smell of butterscotch...or is it vanilla? Either way, make sure to stop and lean in to smell the Ponderosa Pines to decide for yourself (Bob Ross definitely would).

node.text:
Today we are going to learn about an insect with a name that strikes fear in the hearts of some, and amazement in others: the notorious Tarantula Hawk (Pepsis thisbe).

The Tarantula Hawk has is a species of spider wasp that resides, among other places, in the deserts of the southwestern United States. They have a very sleek dark blue body with vibrant amber colored wings, which makes them easy to spot. Despite the name, adult Tarantula Hawks feed on nectar, and are one of the largest pollinators of flowers in the world.

In recent years, the Tarantula Hawk has gained some notoriety as having one of the most painful stings in all the animal kingdom. There is a reason for this sting being so powerful - babies! Well, larvae to be more specific. After mating with a male, the female Tarantula Hawk will go out and hunt for tarantulas. The wasp uses its sting to completely paralyze (not kill) a tarantula. Then, the immobile spider is dragged back to its burrow and the wasp lays her eggs in the its abdomen. When the eggs hatch, the larvae begin the brutal process of eating the tarantula from the inside out, while avoiding vital organs for as long as possible in order to keep the tarantula alive until the larvae pupate. Once the larvae pupate into adults, they emerge from the tarantula’s abdomen, killing it in the process.

🎵It’s the ciiiiircle of liiiiife!🎵

Though their lifecycle can be considered quite gruesome, humans have little reason to worry about the Tarantula Hawk. Despite their painful sting, they pose no threat to us - if you leave them be, they will do the same with you. 

#FindYourPark #EncuentraTuParque

node.text:
As we enter the peak of summer here in Zion National Park, nocturnal predators abound…behold the fearsome Canyon Tree Frog!

Small in stature, adults are only 1-2 inches long. Well camouflaged in this rocky environment and able to cling to perches with adhesive toe pads, the canyon tree frog is on the hunt. Flies, spiders, ants, small invertebrates, and beetles don’t stand a chance, while those that would prey upon this mighty amphibian may never even notice it.

Along watercourses in the park one might hear the males’ loud calls in the first few hours after dark, mostly during the spring and late summer mating seasons. These calls might not be quite what you would expect to hear, with many visitors comparing the sound to sheep, goats, or woodpecker drumming.

During the day, especially when rain is as scarce as it has been, you would be hard pressed to spot them as they shelter in crevices and other protective areas.

Their name belies their true nature as they prefer boulders to trees in most instances and tend to look more like a toad than a frog!

Learn more about the amphibians of Zion National Park here: go.usa.gov/x66k7 and print your own Reptiles and Amphibians Guide from here: go.usa.gov/x66kF

A couple of weeks ago, Zion made news with a flash flood that temporarily blocked the South Entrance to the park. In our area, monsoon weather patterns that can bring strong thunderstorms typically begin in mid-July and last into September. This video, filmed in 2019, shows a small scale flash flood on Oak Creek. 

Flash floods are a real danger and can be life threatening. During a flash flood, the water level rises quickly, within minutes or even seconds. A flash flood can rush down a canyon in a wall of water and debris 12 feet high or more.

In larger canyon systems, like Zion, flash floods are often caused by storms miles away. You should know the weather forecast and flash flood potential before starting your trip. If bad weather threatens, do not enter a narrow canyon.

Flash flood potential is a rating given by the National Weather Service based on the forecast:
Not Expected - Your safety is your responsibility.
Possible - Some slot canyons may experience flooding.
Probable - Some slot canyons are expected to experience flooding.
Expected - Many slot canyons are expected to experience flooding.

You can check this rating at the Visitor Center or online at: https://www.weather.gov/slc/flashflood

Despite the forecast, flooding is possible at any time, and floods have occurred on days that they were not expected. A possible or probable flash flood potential should be a serious cause for concern. 

NPS Video / Brian Whitehead
A two-foot high wall of muddy water flows fast down a creek toward the camera, carrying debris. A second shot shows the flood headwall entering the North Fork of the Virgin River.

Explore. Learn. Protect… is the motto of the Junior Ranger program! 

Did you know that Zion has a Junior Ranger Program for anyone 4 years and older? While exploring the park to complete the Junior Ranger Handbook you will learn interesting things about Zion.  The activity book provides an opportunity for you to explore and learn about our plants, animals and rocks of Zion. You discover ways that you can help protect Zion for future visitors. You are invited to participate by completing an activity handbook which you can pick up at the Visitor Center upon your arrival with your family.

You will need to complete the designated age appropriate pages in the booklet and attend a ranger-led program to earn your Junior Ranger badge from Zion National Park. Becoming a Zion Junior Ranger is a fun way to explore and enjoy Zion National Park and the natural world. Please allow for several hours to complete this booklet as activities include traveling throughout Zion Canyon in search of cool things to discover. 

Upon completion, bring your booklet back to the Visitor Center to be sworn in. You are sworn in by a park ranger by raising your right hand and promising to continue to explore, learn about and protect Zion National Park and all National Parks. The park ranger will present you with your badge. Happy Exploring!

#JuniorRanger #FindYourPark #EncuentraTuParque

If you’ve seen our posts earlier this week, then you are well on your way to Planning Like a Park Ranger! Once you have a plan ready and have safely arrived in Zion, it is time to enjoy your efforts. Now, just remember to do like the flat hats do and keep these final four tips in mind during your visit to Zion: 

💧 Stay hydrated! Bring enough water with you—1 gallon per person per day—and remember to drink it. There are water fill up stations at most of our shuttle stops, and reusable bottles available for sale in park stores. 

🍎 Feed yourself, not the animals! Bring lots of salty snacks to help replenish the nutrients your body loses through sweat to stay hydrated, and make sure you and your friends are the only critters that eat them. Do not approach or touch wild animals, either—for their safety and yours. 

🚫 Hike smart! Remember you are responsible for your own safety - monitor yourself and your buddies for a safe and enjoyable trip. Know the symptoms of heat related illness and take precautions to avoid becoming sick. No hike is worth your health and safety: you can always turn around at any time. 

📍 Leave No Trace! Help us preserve this land for future generations. Carving into rocks and trees or stacking stones takes away from the wild scenery and can damage valuable animal homes and habitats. Take as many photographs as you would like but leave the flowers here for the next visitor to admire. 

Take our #ZionPledge online at www.nps.gov/zion/planyourvisit/zion-pledge.htm to show your commitment to #PlanLikeAParkRanger before your visit to Zion! 

#FindYourPark #EncuentraTuParque

node.text:
Once you’ve followed yesterday’s #PlanLikeAParkRanger tips and made your plan, you’re ready to come to Zion. Now, here are some tips for getting to and arriving at the park, so you can have a more enjoyable experience! 

🎒 Pack your patience - Zion is experiencing record-breaking visitation, so while you are here, expect traffic, long lines for the shuttle, and crowds on trails. Remember that you are part of the crowd, and to have patience with other visitors who are also trying to enjoy their time here.

🏡 Stop at the visitor center - Zion National Park has two visitor centers: one located in Kolob Canyons, close to Cedar City, and one in the main Zion Canyon near Springdale. The Zion Canyon Visitor Center is where you can catch the shuttle that runs along the Scenic Drive. Make sure you’re putting the right visitor center into your GPS, or you could end up in an entirely different area of the park. 

🚗Park in designated areas only - Parking lots in Zion Canyon tend to fill up by 7am, so many visitors park in Springdale and ride the town shuttle to the park. Please be aware of where you are parking; Avoid blocking traffic, never park on vegetation, and leave others room to get out. 

By packing your patience, stopping at a visitor center, and parking in the right spots, you’ll arrive safely to Zion National Park ready for your trip! Check out our page tomorrow for our final tips on how you can Plan Like A Park Ranger. 

#FindYourPark #EncuentraTuParque
